Dear Mayor Mcneill,
Enclosed with this letter is an economic analysis of the decision of whether to keep
MegaTire as a government run monopoly, or to sell it to private companies as one firm or two.
Consumer benefit was used as a measure to determine which option is the best, because we
were informed that your office aims to prioritize this. Consumer benefit being the resulting
satisfaction of the prices and quantities chosen by firms given preferences of consumers for
snow tires.
MegaTire would be operating with lower costs if it were to privatize, due to the business
expertise of the investors. Thus, if it were sold as one firm it would still remain a monopoly,
but would generate a greater consumer benefit than it currently is as a government monopoly.
We therefore recommend selling MegaTire, because in addition to the consumer benefit
increase there is also the gain from the revenue of the sale of the firm.
The firm can be sold as one or two firms. If it were to be sold as two firms it would
create an oligopoly where the two firms would compete for sales. If the two firms were to
compete as regular firms, this would result in an even greater consumer benefit than one firm
acting as a monopoly. However, this competition could lead to the firms working together in
order to push prices and quantities to monopoly amounts. If your office would like to maximize
consumer surplus, they would want to sell MegaTire as two firms, but ensure policies are set
in place to prevent monopolistic practices.
Please let us know if you are in need of any clarifications that we may assist you with.
Sincerely,
Elizabeth Riese
Junior Analyst

Economic Analysis of Privatizing MegaTire
Currently, MegaTire is a government run monopoly without price discrimination that
produces snow tires. If MegaTire were to privatize, it would have two options; to either sell as
a one firm or to sell as two firms. If it were to sell as one firm it would still be a monopoly.
However, it would produce at a lower marginal cost as a private company. If it were to sell as
two firms, it would then create a Cournot Duopoly which means the two firms would then have
choices between different strategies. This analysis aims to determine which of these three
options (i.e. don’t sell, sell as one firm or sell as two firms) is the best given that the Mayor
prefers maximized consumer surplus and revenue from the sale of the firm/firms.
Any monopoly when producing at its optimum quantity and pricing causes the market
it dominates to incur deadweight loss. This means that consumer surplus is not at its maximum,
and the market for snow tires would be inefficient. If Megatire chooses to privatize as one firm,
it would still be a monopoly, but the marginal cost of production would be lower. The
magnitude of the deadweight loss and consumer surplus would thusly increase (Figure 1).
Figure 1 – Difference in magnitudes of surpluses for higher and lower marginal costs for
government monopoly (left) and private monopoly (right) assuming linear demand for snow tires
and constant marginal cost

As a private monopoly, the firm would produce a larger consumer surplus compared to a
government one, but the market would also incur a much greater deadweight loss. The revenue
and producer surplus of the privatized firm would also be greater than that of the government
monopoly. Given that the Mayor wants to maximize consumer surplus despite an increase in
deadweight loss, it can be concluded that a private monopoly would be preferred over a
government-run one.
If the firm were to privatize as two firms it would create an oligopoly which means the
two firms would compete against each other for sales. The firms would then have different
choices in how they interact with one other; they may collude or compete. They would most
likely function as a Cournot Duopoly specifically, because this market would meet all the
definitions of such. It has two identical firms with the same constant marginal costs, and the
firms would most likely compete in quantities rather than prices as other markets for tires do.
Cournot Duopolies have one-shot stages in which both firms make their quantity producing
decisions at the same time. It is not certain that there are infinite stages because it is uncertain
if the companies will last forever. It can however be said that the game is indefinite, because
people will always need snow tires in Tironto, and therefore it can be modelled as an infinite
game. This analysis will assume that snow tires are produced and sold all year round with each
day of price setting being a new stage in the game1. Each firm then has two options: to collude
with one another, or to compete like Cournot firms.
1 Although in reality snow tires are much more popular in the winter time and majority of sales would really be
in that period.

If the firms were to collude, this would result in the same surplus distribution for the
market as the one private monopolist firm. However, each firm would create a constituent half
of each type of surplus. This would mean the consumers experience the same level of surplus
as one private monopolist firm (Figure 2). Therefore, consumers are no better off if the firms
decide this.
This begs the question of whether it would be better for the two firms to function as Cournot
Firms. To do this one can compare the monopoly market quantity with the Cournot equilibrium
quantity in terms of general solutions to see which yields a greater consumer surplus.

equilibrium quantity is greater than the monopoly one. Graphically it can be seen that the
having two Cournot firms would yield a larger consumer surplus than the monopoly ones, but
still with some deadweight loss (Figure 3).
If the Mayor’s main goal is to maximize consumer surplus then it would appear that both firms
acting as Cournot firms is a preferred option to both as monopolies, or just selling as one firm
that acts as a monopoly.
Having one firm act as a monopoly and other as a Cournot firm is still an option also.
Irrespective of what the resulting consumer surplus, it would make sense for the Mayor of
Tironto to create policies that prevent monopolistic collusion practices. This is because the
dominant strategy for both firms would be to act as monopolistic firms. Although the exact
profits from each option are not known, a payoff matrix with arbitrary values in the style of a
prisoner’s dilemma can be constructed to show the relative payoffs for each firm in every case
(Figure 4). The values of the payoffs were chosen to model how both firms would be better off
if they both acted as monopolies rather than Cournot firms, and how if only one did they would
